article.description: Quianna Chaney and Sylvia Fowles each scored 14 points as eighth-ranked LSU breezed by South Carolina.
article.headline: LSU wins eighth straight, remains tied for conference lead
article.linkText: LSU crushes S. Carolina, extends win streak to 8
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- In its previous seven victories, eighth-ranked LSU has been burying opponents at the start of games.

The Lady Tigers took until the second half to deliver the knockout in their eighth straight win, 67-37 against South Carolina on Thursday night.

LSU, which had trailed for a total of 20 seconds during its previous seven games, had an 11-point halftime advantage. The Lady Tigers (17-3, 6-0) ran off a string of 18 points in the second half to build a 58-28 lead.

"I challenged them a little bit at halftime," LSU coach Van Chancellor said. "I didn't think we played with the enthusiasm and the intensity we had been in the first half. In the second half, we played the way LSU ought to play."

The Lady Tigers remained tied for first place with Tennessee in the SEC. All of the victories during the streak have been by at least 11 points. Quianna Chaney and Sylvia Fowles each scored 14 points for the Lady Tigers.

Chaney, who made three 3-pointers, also had four assists and three steals. Fowles, who was 5-of-6 from the field, grabbed a team-high seven rebounds. RaShonta LeBlanc had 10 points and five assists.

Demetress Adams had 15 points and 11 rebounds for the Gamecocks (11-10, 0-6). Jordan Jones, South Carolina's leading scorer, had two points -- 11 fewer than her average coming in.

"LSU did an excellent job defending on the perimeter," South Carolina coach Susan Walvius said. "LSU is a different team in how they defend. Then, the depth and the veterans they have was a big factor in the second half."

LSU fell behind twice by two points in the first 5 1/2 minutes. The Gamecocks, whose last lead was at 8-6, tied the score at 10 on Jones' field goal. The Lady Tigers then took control with an 18-2 run. After a basket by Fowles put the Lady Tigers on top, Chaney hit consecutive 3-pointers.

"I was going to everything I could to help us," Chaney said. "Hitting those threes was a big part of our run in the first half. That got our intensity back."

South Carolina trailed 31-20 by halftime.

The LSU starters played slightly more than 11 minutes in the second half. The Lady Tigers outscored the Gamecocks 27-8 during that stretch to build a 30-point advantage at 58-28. LSU's biggest margin came at 66-30 with the reserves on the court.
